/*
- (1) ...
      It isn't really a matter of "can this be implemented", it's more of a,
      "can this be implemented and not be terribly slow".

      Remember, access to other floating point rounding modes is more of low level
      thing, given that you need to access non-portable processor state with inline
      assembly or some other library that wraps it for you. So most programming 
      languages are stuck with RN, round to nearest.

      Now, you can easily reimplement the hardware routines for the floating point
      rounding modes, it's just going to be slower than the hardware implementation.
      This is called "softfloat", floating point in software.

- (2) Tevador, the creator thinks that it can be done, just really slowly.
      Which he estimates 30 hashes a minute, which is less than 1 H/s.

      That's just, really really low. Like come on!

      I wanted to try beat that.
*/
