- (1) ...

      People have asked me why I would decide to make such a thing, and it's really
      just a "because I wanted to" or because it's a nice engineering problem.

      RandomX being the huge monolith that it is got me very interested, and what
      tevador said really felt like a challenge.

- (2) The point of WebAssembly is to be a compilation target for performance
      sensitive code, it's basically assembly for the web, where you work with raw
      memory, unboxed integers, and so on.

      ... web workers, and they communicate by message passing.

      ... there are a lot of extensions to WASM that actually make it a pretty fast 
      contender over actual instruction sets.
      
      So, JavaScript can execute arbitrary code pretty fast at runtime, you just
      generate WebAssembly just in time, and get JavaScript to load and execute it
      for you!

- (3) There are some downsides, no AES instruction, and you're limited to a fixed
      rounding mode which is round to nearest, you don't have control over it.
      Which is the same as JavaScript, there is also no nice way to really
      model the ability to change the rounding mode, so it's just not in there.

      For AES, you can just reimplement it too, so it's not a big deal either.

      If there was an implementation, for it to be useful on a browser or Node.JS,
      don't even try allocating 2 GiBs, it's just not a reasonable thing, so we're
      suck to light mining.
*/
